The American experience of fundamental law with amendments and judicial review has motivated constitutionalists at times when they were considering the possibilities for their nation's future.[130] It informed Abraham Lincoln during the American Civil War,[u] his contemporary and ally Benito Juárez of Mexico,[v] and the second generation of 19th-century constitutional nationalists, José Rizal of the Philippines[w] and Sun Yat-sen of China.[x] The framers of the Australian constitution integrated federal ideas from the U.S. and other constitutions.[136]
